<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-7-2">
        <title><m>\S 7.2</m>: Limit Laws</title>

				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Let <m>f</m> be a real function and let <m>a</m> be an accumulation point of <m>\text{Dom}(f)</m>.
Prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> exists if and only if for every sequence <m>(p_{n})</m> in <m>\text{Dom}(f) \setminus\{a\}</m> converging to <m>a</m>, the sequence <m>(f(p_{n}))</m> converges, in which case, <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> equals the limit of the sequence <m>(f(p_{n}))</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Let <m>f,g:A \to \mathbb{R}</m> be real functions.
Prove each of the following using Definition 7.1 or Problem 7.12.
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>, then <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}c = c</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}g(x)</m> both exist, then
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to a}(f(x) \pm g(x)) = \lim_{x\to a}f(x) \pm \lim_{x\to a}g(x).
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}g(x)</m> both exist, then
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to a}(f(x) \cdot g(x)) = \lim_{x\to a}f(x) \cdot \lim_{x\to a}g(x).
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> exists, then
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to a}(c \cdot f(x)) = c \cdot\lim_{x\to a}f(x).
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}g(x)</m> both exist and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}g(x) \neq 0</m>, then
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{ g(x)}= \frac{\lim_{x\to a}f(x) }{ \lim_{x\to a}g(x)}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      If <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>b</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}g(x) =b</m>, then
      <me>
        \lim_{x\to a}f(g(x)) = f(\lim_{x\to a}g(x)) = f(b).
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                              Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be real functions with <m>A = \text{Dom}(f)=\text{Dom}(g)</m> and let <m>a</m> be an accumulation point of <m>A</m>.
Prove that if there exists an open interval <m>J</m> containing <m>a</m> such that <m>f(x)=g(x)</m> for all <m>x \in (J\cap A)\setminus \{a\}</m>, then
<me>
  \lim_{x\to a}f(x) = \lim_{x\to a}g(x)
</me>
provided one of the limits exists.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>

                

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>